[{"id":"VH967106","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH967090.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The spheres are isolated from all other objects, and sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is then released from rest. The student says that, assuming the gravitational forces between the spheres are negligible, the kinetic energy of sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> just before it hits sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Y</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> can be determined by multiplying the electric force exerted on sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> at its original position by the distance it moves. Is the student correct? Why or why not?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH967106_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of two spheres, labeled X and Y, both with a radius of R. Sphere X has a charge of positive Q and sphere Y has a charge of negative Q. The centers of the spheres are located at a distance of 10 R apart.  \" height=\"84\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH967090.g01.png\" width=\"290\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q\"><math alttext=\"positive Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and identical sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Y</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q\"><math alttext=\"negative Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The spheres are held with their centers separated by a distance of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"10 R\"><math alttext=\"10 R\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>10</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, as shown in the figure.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, because force times distance equals work, and the work equals the change in kinetic energy.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, because the electric force is the only force exerted if gravity is negligible.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, because the calculation of work must take into account the fact that the force on sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> changes as it moves.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, because the change in kinetic energy can only be determined from the change in potential energy of the system.</p>"],"answer":2}]